      "id": "grammar_articles",
      "type": "grammar_table",
      "title": "Grammatik: Artikler — Articles",
      "explanation": "Danish nouns have two genders: common (en-words) and neuter (et-words). The indefinite article is 'en' or 'et'. The definite article is not a separate word — it is a suffix added to the end of the noun. En-words add '-en', et-words add '-et'. Plurals add '-ene' (most words) or '-erne'. This is one of the most important patterns in Danish.",
      "headers": ["", "Indefinite (a/an)", "Definite (the)", "Plural indefinite", "Plural definite"],
      "rows": [
        { "label": "en-word", "answers": ["en bog", "bogen", "bøger", "bøgerne"] },
        { "label": "et-word", "answers": ["et bord", "bordet", "borde", "bordene"] },
        { "label": "en-word", "answers": ["en stol", "stolen", "stole", "stolene"] },
        { "label": "et-word", "answers": ["et vindue", "vinduet", "vinduer", "vinduerne"] },
        { "label": "en-word", "answers": ["en taske", "tasken", "tasker", "taskerne"] },
        { "label": "et-word", "answers": ["et hæfte", "hæftet", "hæfter", "hæfterne"] }
      ]
