    {
      "id": "cultural_w4",
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Kulturelt hjørne — Danish School Culture",
      "content": "Danish schools have a distinctly informal atmosphere compared to many other countries. Students typically address teachers by their first name — calling a teacher 'hr. Andersen' as in today's reading would be quite unusual in a modern Danish school, where 'Lars' or 'Mette' is the norm. This reflects a broader Danish cultural value called 'lighed' (equality) — hierarchies are deliberately flattened. Students are expected to participate actively, ask questions, and disagree with the teacher. Sitting quietly and waiting to be called on is not the expected behaviour — in fact, silence from a student can be interpreted as disengagement. Group work ('gruppearbejde') is central to Danish pedagogy, and independent critical thinking is valued from an early age."
